text: I think there are two types of persecution here: the physical and emotional. While I don't think Christians are being persecuted physically like in this trailer many sometimes feel persecuted emotionally, and while some will remain silent others can't, which only adds full to the fire, which doesn't help. Me personally, I see comments calling Christians scatterbrained fools it hurts to read, even if the insult is not aimed directly at me. I think that's the main "persecution" (quote on quote) Christians face now a days, whilst in the Middle East it's much more physical and more heart wrenching to see and hear. I'm a Christian and while I'm not being persecuted physically (thank God) it still hurts when I hear folks get insulted for their faith, even if they're not talking to me directly. It's not literal persecution but it still stings the heart none the less so I can see why some Christians feel they are being "attacked". I'm not calling anybody out I'm just trying my best to clarify.

text: These movies have good intent, but they have a serious problem with making Christians look awesome and anyone else terrible. I am a Christian and I do believe that culture has a tendency to hate on Christianity more than other religions purely for the fact that it's radical and has no room for other beliefs. What they don't understand or don't want to accept is that the only kind of religion that can love is one that does not allow others to believe lies. These movies are lies in a way, they show non Christians to all be hateful and rude and ignorant. This is not what the Bible or Jesus taught to do. Love your enemies, pray for those who persecute you, and do this with gentleness and kindness. This isn't a legal battle or a contest, you don't need propaganda. It's a battle of spiritual nature, of love vs pride. The individual needs of each person in the world who feel the pain and valueless side of life without knowing that God made them unique and loves them because of who they are not what they can do or what they have. text: So there's a lot of hate going back and forth on here and I just thought I'd speak my mind. Both parties (christians and nonchristians) have made mistakes. I am a devout Christian. I have a sister who is an open lesbian and I love her the same as I would if my sister were straight. There are Christians out there who would persecute me for that, and there are also nonChristians who would persecute me for that. With that being said it's pretty safe to say that no matter what you believe in the way you choose to behave should have nothing to do witg your religion. More specifically, the way that some Christians behave shouldn't reflect ALL Christians, just as the way certain homosexuals behave, shouldn't reflect ALL homosexuals and so on and so forth. God gives us the choice to excercise free will and I can assure you that anyone who tells you that you're going to hell will find themselves in hell ass well. Many people just in general tend to use the bible as a means to bully others. They twist the word of God to support their own ideologies. The fact is that God simply commanded us to love one another...period. God didn't say "Love your brother if he's straight. Love your sister, but she can't be black. Love your brother as long as he believes what you believe in." I think as Christians we should get back to focusing on what God wanted from us. Simply put...we need to love each other. No exceptions and no questions asked. So if you are a nonbeliever, and you are reading this, I apologize on the behalf of all the Christians who have failed to see the purpose of the religion they claim to be rallying for. God bless

text: I liked the first film, but I think this one is taking it a bit over the edge. And to everyone else persecuting Christian beliefs after seeing this trailer, you have to remember that this is a movie firmly advocating all Christian beliefs. It's not trying to bring balance between Atheists, Jews, Muslims, and Christians alike, it's saying that "We're Christians, and this is what we believe in whether you like it or not." Of course it's going to be strongly biased! So if you aren't open to the values of Christianity, then you probably won't like the movie. Pure Flix is a CHRISTIAN entertainment company that makes CHRISTIAN films. That being said, however, this one puts to much pity on Christians in my opinion and makes them look way to victimized. text: The idea that the First Amendment is "Seperation of Church and State" is quite the liberal phrasing and misrepresentation of the Constitution.  It is quite easy to land here because this is what liberal high school textbooks on social studies in American History.  I actually thought this for a long time due to my education.  But read the actual Constitution.  It is the restricting of government from meddling with the practice of religion.  There is no cross-reference to the church staying out of government.  "Seperation of Church and State" is revisionist to the Constitution.   The First Amendment: "Congress shall make no law respecting an establishment of religion, or prohibiting the free exercise thereof; or abridging the freedom of speech, or of the press; or the right of the people peaceably to assemble, and to petition the government for a redress of grievances."

You can quote the Prophet Muhammad all day in school, or Buddha as well as many other religious figures, and yet if someone quotes any one from the Bible, it is seen as Christians trying to force their believes on others.  I find it truly sad when Not just America but any nation that claims liberty and freedom as staples of society gets to the point when people are forced to keep who they are private because it may offend some one.  Who is more offensive?  The person who simply incorporates things that are part of who they are in their every day life, or the person that hates that characteristic (Religion in this case) so much that they insist that the other person should not be allowed to express that part of their life in public in any way.  if that characteristic  was sexual orientation or something along the lines of transgender, then it would be a whole other story, it would be seen as bigotry, and prejudice, but when it is Christianity (which if you are a christian then it is who you are not something you claim to be) people dont look at both sides of the coin.

text: Atheists don't want to ban the Bible. You can't understand the literature or historical culture of any civilization without the aid of their belief system. You can't understand all the allusions in Shakespeare and Dante's Divina Commedia without the aid of the Bible. These opinions about atheists stem purely from the delusion that we are persecuting Christians. What we are actually asserting is the right of children to have unbiased, unindoctrinated critical thinking about the world and morality. How many LGBT individuals are kicked out of their homes, or worse, commit suicide because the religious community ostracise them? These communities care more about their own self-preservation into the supposed afterlife than about the humans around them. This is what we are trying to stop. We are all for your right to believe anything you want, but the moment you try and indoctrinate highly impressionable children and telling them not to think for themselves because religion knows all the answers, then it becomes a problem.

text: Here's the intriguing thing for me:   The central passage of Scripture in this movie is the passage where Jesus commands his followers to "love" their enemies and "pray for those who persecute" them (Matthew 5:43-48; see also Luke 6:27-38).   The ethic being advanced in these sayings of Jesus is one that is sorely needed during this current election year in the US: People too often have been advancing the terrible ethic "hate your enemies," and people have even been identifying those who *aren't* their enemies as their enemies.   Notice Jesus' statement here as Matthew presents it: "For if you love those who love you, what reward do you have? Do not even the tax collectors [a class of people who often took advantage of people] do the same? And if you greet only your siblings, what more are you doing than others? Do not even the Gentiles do the same?" (Matthew 5:46-47).  ^ This doesn't sound to me like Jesus is promoting a persecution complex. The call to responsibility in this "love your enemies" passage in the Sermon on the Mount is not placed by Jesus on the *enemies* of his followers—Jesus is address his followers here, not their enemies (actual enemies or those they might wrongly perceive to be their enemies).   The tone I see in this trailer (much like the tone in the last movie) sounds very much like, "We poor Christians are being persecuted!" Personally, I don't think that's the attitude Jesus was advocating. First Peter 4:15 also contains some advice from a first-or-second-century Christian to other Christians to be careful whether they are "suffering as a Christian" or suffering "as a meddler in the affairs of others." Kind of important and timely, I think.

text: You can make a movie that characterizes Atheists exactly how your flawed logic perceives us, but putting words in our mouths doesn't make your argument stronger, it makes it weaker. This wave of Christian propaganda films is part of a last ditch effort to maintain the power of superstitious nonsense in the US. This movie is pure strawman BS! We don't think God is dead, nor do we hate him, we just don't think he ever existed in the first place. This doesn't mean that with this belief we go on to live hateful and unfulfilled lives, it just means that we don't believe in God. Our lives are defined by what we believe, not what we don't believe. I think neither Atheists or Christians believe in the Easter Bunny, but is your life defined by a lack of belief in the Easter Bunny? I'm not trying to trivialize, but if somebody was trying to force their Easter Bunny belief on you, and make it part of everyday politics by blurring the line between Easter Bunny and State, you would be pretty annoyed too, right?

text: It's so sad how many people buy into the modern fable that science has somehow replaced religion. Religion provides something that science can never go near: a code of ethics. Religious teachings are profound revelations about the human condition. Americans don't realize how much the teachings of Jesus are woven into the fabric of their laws, behavior, and culture. For example, the Puritans led the abolitionist movement because they had reason to believe that every human being is valuable because they are made in the image of God. They also spearheaded the campaign for public education. They didn't do any of this because they were students of Darwin, but Jesus. Do not claim to champion "fact" if you are prepared to disregard history, your own experience of your humanity, and our collective human experience.

text: The Bible spends very little time addressing HOW we are here (though it  is actually astonishingly insightful in that regard if viewed for what  it is). It is instead dedicated to the questions of what we are and WHY  we are here. And yet it is treated and dismissed as if it is all a long  winded attempt to explain natural phenomena. Science is one kind of  revelation, religion is another. One is concerned with outward human  observation (limited as it is), the other with inward human  experience (more expansive and extraordinary because it is the one  thing we understand most intimately). They can't compete with one  another because they are not playing the same game. Disregard religion  and you throw out our most extensive exploration into the human  intuition that makes society possible: morality. Science can tell you  that we are the most remarkably complex thing in the known universe, but  it cannot tell you what to do with that knowledge.

text: It's sad to see why so many people have fallen into the egoistic modern mindset. Thinking that because they are strong in science and are the "latest evolutionary species" and the "most intelligent" and are not "traditional and outdated", they'd see religion as outdated. The idea of God is outdated? Science proves that God doesnt exist? big bang and evolution proves that God doesnt exist? Science is only the study of what is, and what could have been. Patterns, systems, the way things work. But it is not history. Yes the universe we currently have takes millions of years to come to where it is today. That's the process. But did it occur? Maybe not. People fail to see that whether or not the earth seems to be billions of years old, could have been already created that way. If God created the earth when its age according to science is 0 years old, and put humans on it right away, would the environment be appropriate for life to be sustained? That would make God a fool and would directly contradict the fact that He is able to create everything yet not look into this matter. Science can explain the current ongoing process (but still not be able to explain a million other mysteries about this world), but it does not prove the origin of everything. Big bang's origin is a bang. Where did the big bang come from? some even believe that the universe is expanding, and prior to the big bang, it was converging and expanding like a spring. So.. does that explain the origins of all things? no. Science merely explains what could have been and what currently is. To say that God does not exist because of such "theories" or "facts" does not disprove God.   If scientist were to go back to our day of creation by time travel, do a biological test on day 1 of Adam's existence, they'd go like "oh it seems base on science, he is 30 years old approximately (just hypothetical age for illustration) and he is an adult. He must have lived 30 years already." This is what scientists and atheists are doing. Yes on that day he may be 30 years old already based on science, but did he live the past 30 years? They can explain what could have been but they cannot say it indeed happened as a fact unless there were witnesses that such events did happen such as Adam being born from another human who was born from another and another originating from an ape right back to the first organism on this earth.  People are condemning those who believe in a God, while holding fast to science. Yet they cannot see that science cannot exist by itself. Laws do not create themselves. Governments can enact a set of law. A body establishes laws or regulation. Organisations come up with their rules and regulations that all must comply to. In the case of religion and God, scientist are claiming that humans are living and all nature is how it is today, the ecosystem working this way, the blood carrying food and oxygen to our cells, etc etc all because of science (the law). And according to this "law", it seems like the earth is billions of years old therefore there is no God. Who created the laws? who established them? did science create itself to establish that one S shell in an atom should contain how many electrons?What people are doing is just believing in the law and claiming that there is no one who established such laws. Many theories have been discovered. Anti-matter etc. Even if they could prove big bang was caused by such things, where did they come from? what scientific laws did this things comply to? did they exist by themselves?  Science and God goes hand in hand. To say science contradicts the idea of God or disproves God's existence is just throwing a point without considering the bigger picture. To say God is an imaginary friend and asking us to prove that He exist by showing us a very clear sign or show himself is just not any different than me thinking that another person's brains doesnt exist and requires him to show it to me. I wont believe it till I see it and feel it. Of course to meet such a demand is outrageous, unless that person has died or has his skull smashed and his brains ooze out and I so happen to witness it. But to say that person has no brains? imaginary brains, are they? Of course people would argue and say "oh based on autopsy on other dead people it shows that humans have brains, based on  CT scan of this person he has his brains, etc etc. But that's not giving me direct proof of a specific person's brain. What if there were an alien inside instead of a brain? Of course I'd have to have faith and believe that based on biological facts established from other human bodies, and the way CT scans work, I come to believe this person has a brain.   What about God? To say "oh he is just imaginary" or "I dont see him so I dont believe" or "So many people are suffering, proves that God doesn't exist" is just naive. If you want to see the reason as to why people claim a God exist, delve deeper into religious teachings and writings and start seeing the bigger picture by seeing the strong points from science and religion or philosophy. See the world and think. People love the easy way out and be bias with their source of information without much consideration. Considering only so little facts or easily succumb to brainwashing information from others. It is easy to say God doesn't exist just by looking at the surface. I'd definitely not believe a person has brains if he kept saying stupid statements if I were to not learn science and not want to dig deeper into science.   I believe in a God. Science is still slowly uncovering many things about this world, but it can only go as far as the humans mind can perceive it.

text: It is easy to say that there's no proof for any story when someone doesn't think it's true, but the way I look at it is any story can be true even if there's no proof for it. things like this do happen in school, and then they are taken to a court or school board and are publicly wronged. I think as a human that if anyone believes in a god, then they have every natural right to answer any question of a student on that matter with a yes or no, but to quote from the Bible on the question it can cause some big baby parents to get upset. my personal response to the movie is that yes it goes over board with the idea that courts would deal with this kind of matter, but some atheists have an anger that builds up in their hearts because of a death of a loved one, or because of something they just don't like about "religion." to be fair I don't think all atheists are angry at the idea of a god, even so they just have a more generally accepted philosophy on life that is not bound by just belief or faith in the unseen. For all the " it takes a community to raise a child" socialist out there, what if someone answers your child's religious question and tells your child a basic quote, "love your enemy as yourself" how would that make you feel, I mean it's not like he/she is your enemy or anything, this is what it means to love your enemy even the one that you just don't like, it means to set aside your pride of life, looks and differences and be kind and gentle to them even if they hurt you. really all the bible talks about in the old testament is that if you move on to someone else's property and aren't able to pay then you have to serve them seven years until the debt is paid in off in labor. most people who talk about that bible and turn it into a bad book don't actually know what they are saying, for example the old testament talks about how at that time period kings would use their gods to divide the nations so that  they could conquer them, but God saw what they were doing to his people ( the Israelites) he had them  kill the opposing nations. I'm only stating facts from what I read in the bible, but if I were to agree that what people believe must stay in there minds and out of the schools then that would make me a comfort conformist and a socialist. this statement is a comment to some of the comments posed, and to react to my comment would only be to make yourself feel good about your pride, beliefs, thoughts on this comment or rejection of it so please think before you post.

text: Alright a lot of you guys are taking it too to heart this movie is about certain people as was the first one. Christians are never on the bandwagon train that all athiest are bad or as presented in these two movies. In fact there are isolated cases much like the ones in these films. But these are all true things that Christians experience. If anyone has a persecution complex its you guys who feel the need to make it a point that somehow this movie is about atheist as a whole. Self centered much? Anytime a movie comes out with a bad atheist you guys flock together with a "mess with one of us mess with all of us" attitude but are the first ones to bail on eachother when an athiest misrepresents you. Well tough there are good and bad athiest. You guys criticise Christians for the same things but there's no such things as bad Christians. There's Christians and fakes who call themselves Christians but aren't. Get that straight. Deal with the fact that we choose to speak out about very real things we experience more often than not with bad athiest. Not saying at all that all athiest are the same. I've met some extremely reasonable people but in my honest experience I've delt with more of the bad than the good. But this movie aint about all of you its about all of the bad ones that misrepresent you.   Plus we Christian folk are always misrepresented in movies and tv. You don't see us throwing fits with hateful comments like a lot of you have. And we've had to deal with being treated as crazy religious folk as a result of that. And we aren't that at all. Real Christian folk don't disown their kids for coming out as gay, real Christians don't go hating on others we don't go labeling others. All the hateful things done all of the discrimination that we see done by people who "represent" God don't. The very real loving and merciful God that true Christians represent is above all of that. We're all in this together so deal with it at least we are representing a very real example of people in our films. We say it as it is and everything said by one of the athiest just in this trailer is something I've either heard on a personal level or known through someones else that it happened to. Its not as dramatic as the film of course.  The film isn't a true story. Its only based on things we've delt with and things the Bible says we will deal with even more in the coming future. So just let it be jeeze.

text: Serious question about the plot of this film.  The beginning seems to describe a terrible world where 'prayer in school' is banned.  This is supposed to be today's world, but that's not the case.  School mandated prayer is banned, because it can alienate non-Christian students.  If you are a student, you can pray all you want, you just can't force anyone else to do it and the school can't mandate it.  And even if you could, shouldn't you prefer private personal prayer?  Doesn't Matthew 6.5 state "And when you pray, do not be like the hypocrites, for they love to pray standing in the synagogues and on the street corners to be seen by others. Truly I tell you, they have received their reward in full."

text: I LOVED the first movie and while I am not religious by any means, I do have faith and having at least a little bit of hope in your heart is why I believe movies like this continue to touch those with similar beliefs and exist. You don't have to believe to see this film, it's just an inspirational movie that many can relate to. Being silenced is a harsh feeling to come across. It's a reality that everyone faces in some point in time. It hurts. Don't sit there and criticize a film that gives hope to people; believers or not. There's a broader message being spread throughout these films (especially the first one). Don't shut people down just because you are annoyed by their belief. Sure, there's many that push their beliefs on people, but that's not the point. There's things that YOU believe that many may not necessarily agree with. I like these films because they question the unknown. WE DON"T KNOW, but we BELIEVE and that's what matters in the end. I don't understand how people can be so hateful because of a simple movie. Don't watch it if it's too hard for you to understand. It's an ongoing question being pushed on people for many years now; I like to think this gives light on the topic and why people turn away from the message and why it keeps getting banned from everything. It's sad that sensitivity has destroyed humanity. I remember the world when you could praise the lord and still live your life. I'm sorry that not many of you can turn your cheek and keep living your life the way you please as well. Just get over yourselves and live and stop judging and making the world a more complicated place. This is why we can't have nice things.

text: Boy, that like-dislike ratio says a whole lot about the quality of these movies.  I'm a Christian, and even though I'd probably side with the Defendant in this scenario, I highly doubt that those who try to silence Christianity are as two-dimensional as many of the Youtube comments on this video.  I want to recommend this movie, and its predecessor, but I simply can't do that for non-Christians.  Honestly, it looks like the best thing I'll be able to say about this movie is that, if we're not careful, this fictional, at least slightly exaggerated scenario could become a reality one day.  Heck, contrary to what many of the comments assert, Christians in the West are being singled out and attacked for publicly expressing their beliefs.  The ACLU, mentioned in this trailer, is notorious for fighting against Christians' right to religious freedom, going so far as to sue the USCCB in order to force it to cooperate in providing abortion-related treatment.  I don't know the exact details, but I do know that it's an attack on religious freedom if ever I saw one.  The USCCB has always asserted that abortion is morally wrong and cannot and ought not to be condoned.  So to force them to cooperate with providing abortion-related treatment is an attack on religious freedom.  You could argue that abortion is a woman's right and that denying it is unconstitutional, but that's not the point I'm trying to make here.  The point is that if the ACLU can sue a group of Christians to try and force them to participate in something they believe to be morally wrong and no one bats an eye, then there's something very wrong here.  If the trailer is anything to judge by, then the only thing you should take seriously about this movie is that this could be our future.  I plan to see this (eventually) and see for myself what they get wrong...and what they get right.

text: Now that I've had some time to cool off and think, there are some things I'd like to say about this movie.  Now, I don't hate Christians.  In fact, some Christians I've known were good and decent people who aside from a difference in opinion regarding certain matters were actually quite acceptable company.  But....I loathe this movie and I despise those who made it and those who call it a great film.  Here's why:  1) This movie is a propaganda film straight out of Joseph Goebbel's handbook that uses fear tactics to create an absolutionist mindset in it's audience.  The entire message is that if you're Christian then anyone whose not a Christian will persecute and punish you for your beliefs because at best, non-Christians are bitter and misguided or downright evil at worst.  And even if you are Christian, if you don't agree with everything this movie says than you're automatically going to hell.  2) The kind of Christians who made this film, as well as those who watch it, are the reason why I became an Atheist.  These kind of Christians are the ones who claim to follow Christ but only possess a rudimentary knowledge of both him and Christianity, who demand others tolerate their beliefs but have zero respect for anything that lies outside of their own narrow world view, who demand kindness but wouldn't hold the door open for someone in a wheelchair, who rather than follow Christ's example of trying to make the world a better place use their faith as a means to feel superior to others, and who preach morality but practice it only when it's convenient for them.  3) It completely misinterprets the meaning of the title.  When Nietzche said, "God is dead and we have killed him," it was actually a fear that the scientific advancements made during his lifetime was too much too soon for humanity's own good.  And while he himself didn't believe in God, Nietzche feared that if the unready masses realized that there was no higher power watching over them to give both a reason to their lives or a guide to base their moral compasses on, the result would be a society driven by nihilism where creativity and advancement ground to a halt in favor of hedonistic self indulgence.  This forms the basis for Nietzche's concept of the "ubermensch" or "over man," an individual who lives by his own morality and standard rather than that of the majority and who is able to accept the initial meaninglessness of life without losing either his dignity or his ability grow and change.

text: See the movie. I Saw the movie. Listen...freedom of speech is on trial here. Its a freedom for everyone. There are precedents being set today in courts around the world. Regular people, but unwittingly misdirected by lack of knowledge are against Christians. And then there are others that act in an  evil way ...are people that are directed by dark forces that exist, are regular everyday people that are being used to manipulate by cunning ways - because they have not see a real Christian yet...live and give and love...and are sadly moved to hurt a free society. If you haven't had an experience with God yet fine. But don't knock the one that has. It seems phony to unbelievers...but its true, cause I once was one....until SOMETHING HAPPENED. The supernatural world is real...not aliens...and sci fi stuff...but the God is love stuff. When the world finally sees Christians standing up for love and what they believe in ...When the world sees this---when the unbelievers finally see this--- they will stop hating them and open their eyes to the truth and work along side of them, not hate them. Christians are a great benefit to all societies and Jesus even told hem to obey the governments over them as to show their obedience to God, above, who governs all things. To pay to Caesar what is his and pay to God what is God...its a win win. However, when a government no longer allows the freedom to believe for all men that choose to believe...then we should pray and see ways to change the laws that hinder that freedom.  The unbelievers that watched Mother Teresa of Calcutta closely---caused them to totally change their thinking and their lives and finally believed in love...perhaps not God all the way...at first, but at least in love and the possibility that God is alive cause they saw His presence in her face and in the face of those receiving that love. Its a far cry from other religions that say kill everyone that doesn't believe like you do...that is not a religion but an ugly ideology. For this life we came here to love not to kill. I pray that all the doubters reading this to ask God to show himself to them...to yes, pray to God and say...Please reveal yourself to me...I want to believe in something more than this awful life of unkindness, greed, and chaos.  Melissa Joan Hart did a good job in acting. Very believable. I came out of the theater singing the song. Dear ones,  If we don't stand up now what will become of the next generation. We must remember our Christian forefathers had to run away from their country for a better world...they created it with God's help. They came to this country for religious and political freedom. Where will our children and grandchildren run to next if we don't stand up for what we believe? The moon? It as to happen now and it has to happen where you live now. Trouble follows you everywhere...stop running people.  Start telling your story, start giving your testimony in the highways and byways. Teens share your faith at school. Pray at lunch two by twos. Pray every night, during the night and in the daytime...Pray for the conversion of souls. People need the Lord. JEsus is kind, forgiving, loving, patient and will accept you where you are!. Why are people afraid of that? One reason because, like he said to the woman caught in adultery when she was about to be stoned...all the people walked away when he said...let those without sin cast the first stone...they walked away...but what did He say to her..."Go and sin no more." People don't want to stop their sinning. That's why people want to choose other religions...cause they feel they can sin and sin...that they shouldn't repent. God is holy. He wants us Holy. In this movie the teacher kept the rules of the school board...and just answered a question about a legally historical figure...just like anyone else in the history books. We have a right, so far, to speak of this wonderful person of Jesus. But in the spiritual rhelm we must go further than just a historical man, we must tell what we have seen and heard as Christians. That is our gospel to the world too. St. Paul said I am not ashamed of the gospel.  The great sin of the American churches is that they are silent at work, silent in the universities, silent in their neighborhoods and silent even at home. Jesus said proclaim the gospel through to the ends of the earth! He gave us a command to love one another, love our enemies, feed them if need be.Christians are called to stand for the good. They are trying to follow laws of love. Atheists must stand with Christians...Why is it ,  just because they don't believe in Jesus..why do they resist this idea? They should look at the common Christians life. Christians should be the first to comfort, reassure, embrace the homeless, the unlovely ,  helpless widow, abandoned orphans, children being used in sextrades and those on the fringe of society. When is that hard to believe or side with? Unless one believes in evil?  Perfect love casts out all fear. This is how the world will recognize us ....by how we love one another...one last question... What makes the best sense to the world is that it needs love...and that grace and power can only come from God himself...cause we can see what, man without God, is capable of so I ask, "Who do you say Jesus is?"

text: This entire situation is ridiculous! "She said Jesus now she's gonna get fired because of it! You should be allowed to speak your mind!" There are so many things wrong with this movie, but just to name a few: #1 Unrealistic situation; a teacher wouldn't be fired for showing favoritism to one religion, she'd simply be reprimanded and given a warning. #2 Apparently Christianity trumps all; if teachers went around preaching other beliefs to their children like Islam, super pro-choice views, etc. some Christians would flip shit! But hey, as long as it goes along with what they believe who cares, right? Because apparently Christianity is the highest, truthful power in the world and decides everything. #3 Forcing beliefs down others' throats; holy shit it's like they don't know when to stop! These characters seem to think that they're handing students the keys to heaven by making them listen to this chick's religious beliefs, but if a teacher were to say that being gay isn't a choice or is "okay", suddenly they're the victims. They're always the victims apparently. "How dare you repress and offend us!" #4 No one's telling you not to be Christian; your religion is your business, just don't go around showing favoritism to one religion when you're in a position of authority or someone is just sick and tired of hearing about it! #5 You're faith really isn't under attack; the problem is you forcing and encouraging your beliefs when it's making your students very uncomfortable. A lot more where that came from, but just to be brief. Btw, I'm a Christian so don't go saying that I feel this way because I'm atheist, bitches.

text: I'm an Atheist, and I do understand this message. However, this entire premise is incredibly, outright, unrealistic to real life. Yes, if this situation happened in real life it would be bad, and Atheists would have to take the blame, and yes an Atheist like myself would have to come out and defend Christians, and yes I would defend Christians if this happened. But... this just... doesn't happen, or at least at a very minuscule level, and that's what makes this movie so cringy. The majority of the portrayal of Atheist's in this movie are nowhere close to being relatable to myself, or any Atheist's I know. So in my view, the fact that Atheists are being portrayed this way is almost discriminatory against Atheists. In conclusion, I just hope that when Christians watch this movie they don't get the wrong impression of how the majority of Atheists actually are. Yes there are bad Atheists, Stalin was one, and I understand that there are plenty more, but the majority are normal, walking, breathing, thinking, lunch eating, friend making, loving, caring, money spending, money making, knowledge gaining, Human Beings.

text: the statement "god is dead" has nothing to do with god being alive or dead, what it means is that mankind no longer needed god to explain how humans came to rule the world. it was a statement of how far natural philosophy (later called "science") had progressed in explaining the world we live in. once upon a time people didn't understand how diseases spread, where they came from, and the like, they believed it was from the wrath of god or from evil spirits. many things in the world used to be explained by magic or by gods, but at a certain point people figured out the answers to these unanswered questions. and the answers lead away from the idea that there was a god directly intervening in the world. thus the statement by nietzche that "god is dead".

text: Okay, so I'm gonna clear some stuff up. Minor spoilers ahead. Just forewarning you readers. This movie isn't about how Christians think we're so oppressed by America or anything like that. The student that asked the question about Jesus saying "Love your enemy" was an atheist and grew up in an atheist home. Her brother died, and while she was going through his stuff, she found his Bible. She begins to read it and sees that her brother had made notes along the way. So she just asks the question. Eventually, her parents find out, and decide to sue for mostly financial reasons. I doubt they even cared about the actual reason they were suing the teacher. Hope that cleared some stuff up about the movie, it really is a great movie. So if you haven't seen it yet and are considering it, I'd recommend it. Thanks for reading, those of you that did. :-)

text: People are so blind nowadays. They say "Science proves God doesn't exist." They say "Science has provided us a real religious system" Where, in fact, they are wrong. The Bible was written *very* long ago, we all can agree? That's proven? Thumbs up all around? That would mean the Bible was written before many scientific advancements and discoveries. Now listen to me here, When we humans thought the earth was held by a giant animal (1500-ish B.C), the bible dictated that "He hangs the earth upon nothing." (Job 26:7) This would mean the Bible told us about the earth being just a rock in space when everyone though it was held by a large animal. The Bible also tells us the earth was round, when everyone thought the earth was flat. "It is he who sits upon the circle of the earth" (Isaiah 40:22). It is also fun to note that Columbus based his expedition on the scriptures.  To quote my source entirely: "Solomon described a "cycle" of air currents two thousand years before scientists "discovered" them. "The wind goes toward the south, and turns about unto the north; it whirls about continually, and the wind returns again according to his circuits" (Ecclesiastes 1:6)."  " The great biological truth concerning the importance of blood in our body’s mechanism has been fully comprehended only in recent years. Up until 120 years ago, sick people were "bled," and many died because of the practice. If you lose your blood, you lose your life. Yet Leviticus 17:11, written 3,000 years ago, declared that blood is the source of life: "For the life of the flesh is in the blood."  "Most cosmologists (scientists who study the structures and evolution of the universe) agree that the Genesis account of creation, in imagining an initial void, may be uncannily close to the truth" (Time, Dec. 1976).  Sources:  https://www.livingwaters.com/witnessingtool/scientificfactsintheBible.shtml  http://www.eternal-productions.org/101science.html  So tell me, non-believers, why are these phrases and passages in the Bible thousands of years before Scientific advancement.

text: I think this film is ridiculous. Christians are not persecuted in America. And this movie is just ridiculous and horrible and arggh!  But I also have to say that I don't understand, why Religion should be banned completly out of schools. I live in Germany and schools here offer a clas named Religion. Because most people here are christians it's about Christianity. At my school you can take catholic and protestant Religion class. But you don't have to take it. If you are an atheist oder a muslem or a jew or a hindu or a buddhist or what ever, you don't have to take it. I don't take it anymore, eventhough I'm catholic, because I think it's boring. But a friednd of mine is an atheist and goes to this Religion class because she wants to learn about the Religion. On my school you also have to take a class called ethnics from grade 7 to grade 10. In this subject you learn about morals, social standards, different cultures and societies and religions. We learnd there about the beliefs of the Islam, Christianity, Jewry, Hinduism and Buddhism. I think, it is important to learn about all these Religions, cultures etc., so you can understand the people and countries better and to be more openminded. The teachers don't preach to us (well, exept in Religion class, the teacher there is a priest, but you are doing it voluntary), they just teach us what the beliefs, traditions, morals etc. of the other religions are. And I think it's really interessting.

text: This movie has so many factual inaccuracies, strawman arguments, false analogies, logical fallacies, but I'm just going to bring up one here:  you can't be arrested and sanctioned simply for mentioning Jesus (or any religioius person/tenet, for that matter) in a public school. It's only when you use public resources and the government in some way to proselytize or force others to follow a particular religion (whether it's actual indoctrination, mandated school prayers, or whatnot) that you can get into serious trouble. Even though all of this should be obvious by now, I'm not also not going into:  a) How this movie portrays all the negative stereotypes of Atheists and the ACLU in practically one go; b) How this movie actually avoids real scientific and philosophical arguments for the existence of God (oh the irony in the title!)  ....because doing so would take far longer than what would be allowed in a youtube comment.

text: Many evolutionists claim that natural selection is the process that drives fish-to-philosopher evolution. Amoeba-to-architect evolution requires that, over time, living things must add more information to their DNA as they gain new features, abilities, or structures. However, natural selection actually works in the opposite direction of what molecules-to-man evolution requires. It selects from already-existing genetic information, and cannot generate new genetic information.  God created the original animal kinds with much diversity in their DNA, so that as they reproduced and filled the earth, their descendants were able to adapt to many different environments. Scientists have observed this—animals reproduce “after their kind” (dogs have puppies, cats have kittens, geese have goslings, kangaroos have joeys, etc.). The genetic makeup of some members of a kind is more suitable to certain environments. Natural selection is the process by which animals die out when they don’t have the genetic makeup that allows them to survive in their environment.  Those animals that survive reproduce more animals like themselves. For example, many animals that live in drier regions of the world are able to gain most of the water they need from the plants they eat. Animals without this ability would have a harder time trying to survive in that region, and would eventually die out. Natural selection is not a process that changes molecules into men over millions of years. Natural selection may bring about a new species of animal, but it cannot generate a new kind of animal.

text: Hello, You don't need to believe in evolution to do science.You need to believe in evolution to do evolutionary science,which some Christians have accepted.Science works perfectly without any connection to evolution. The rise of technology is not due to a belief in evolution, either. Computers, cellular phones, and DVD players all operate based on the laws of physics, which God created. It is because God created a logical, orderly universe and gave us the ability to reason and to be creative that technology is possible. How can a belief in evolution (that complex biological machines do not require an intelligent designer) aid in the development of complex machines, which are clearly intelligently designed? Technology has shown us that sophisticated machines require intelligent designers—not random chance. Science and technology are perfectly consistent with the Bible, but not with evolution. Many people do not realize that science was actually developed in Christian Europe by men who assumed that God created an orderly universe. If the universe is a product of random chance , there is really no reason to expect order in nature. Many of the founders of the principle scientific fields, such as Bacon, Galileo, Kepler, and Newton, were believers in a created earth. The idea that science cannot accept a creationist perspective is a denial of scientific history.

text: One of the latest claims of “evolution in action” comes via a new study of the lowly bedbug. The Wall Street Journal reports that the pests “are quickly evolving to withstand the pesticides used to combat them.”  As creationists often try to explain, such resistance is not evolution in the molecules-to-man sense. The survival of the bedbugs that are resistant to pesticides shows only natural selection, or “selective survival” of certain variations of bedbugs.  Some of the creatures already possessed resistance to the pesticide via variations in their DNA, which they had as a result of mutations or God’s original created diversity. The survivors then passed along their resistance to their descendants, while those that did not possess the resistance died.  Contrary to the impression left by the media, no new genetic information was added to change bedbugs into a new type of organism. They are still bedbugs. Their resistance to pesticides points to the incredible designs that God gave His creatures so that some could survive and thrive, even in a fallen world.

Melissa Joan Harts character violated a law. Period. Honestly, I think that religion in public schools is a bad idea. Things should remain neutral. text: Dear Friends, I've just finished watching this film on Netflix. It's very American! The film is about a history teacher who is taken to court for talking about Jesus in her classroom.  Part of me was squirming inside as I watched. Typical Christian type of film? Yes, I was indeed embarrassed and uncomfortable as I watched it, but I was determined to see it through.  Why was I squirming? Why was I comfortable? Maybe I've become to cool to talk about Jesus in an open and direct manner?  Maybe I've become sophisticated instead of childlike.  Maybe I dont like looking stupid in front of people?  The truth is this woman risked her job rather than deny her LORD who had always loved her and cared for her.  I sense that in the West, we must either die to our sophistication or else accept being silenced by the atmosphere of the society and media around us.  It's time for us to become childlike once again. Little children have no grasp of sophistication, they simply say what they are thinking........  Watch the film on NETFLIX.   Make up your own mind........  Chris Moyler

text: I actually watched this all the way through on Netflix as I wanted to get an insight into how the other side thinks for two reasons: 1) it is always possible I might have something wrong that another perspective could put right and 2) you can better argue your own case if you understand the other side.  I must say, it's a huge disappointment. There was absolutely no subtlety or nuance and the entire film was one giant illustration of the Christian persecution complex. All the atheists/non-Christians (apart from the defence lawyer and he seemed to be moving towards Christianity) were shown as mean-spirited, shallow and self-obsessed to the point of caricature. We were asked to believe that two parents who had lost a son didn't even give a damn because they were atheist, we had all of the school staff and legal team being shown as not only not religious but militantly atheist. In contrast, every one of the Christians was shown to be impossibly polite and innocent at all times. No attempt was made to capture the reality that the world is really made up of shades of grey. Pretty much every character in the film was either a die-hard atheist who didn't just happen to believe in God but actively hated Christianity or a fully committed born again Christian. How is that even slightly reflective of reality?   In addition, the premise of the film (that a teacher would be dragged through the courts for a minor infraction like that) is laughable. However, actually it IS technically true that she broke the rules. She quoted from scripture with no qualification such as "Christians believe that..." and then offered up a Christian view of Christ's good character. That is preaching not teaching and it does conflict with the separation of church and state. I don't think though that anyone would have seriously made a huge fuss about it and the very least she'd have got would've been a slap on the wrist by the headteacher.  The thing which was genuinely not ok though was how she talked privately outside school and didn't attempt to refer the child for counselling or anything like that but, again, preached her religion. I don't know how things usually are in the US but it would be considered highly unprofessional in the UK for a teacher to be meeting with a child outside of school full stop, let alone trying to convert them!

text: The ACLU has stood with Christians in the past in several cases. Including one defending a schoolboys right to read the bible in school. But in this movie it is portraying the ACLU as the bad guys.This is because the people who made this movie and the people this movie is made for have a massive persecution complex. Now you could argue; "But at the end they show a list of court cases that help prove this movies point." Well they do show a list of court cases. But they are all complete nonsense. For example: The case of Cochran v. City of Atlanta case. This case is about a fire chief getting in trouble because he was handing out a self published book about Christianity to his coworkers. These coworkers did not ask for it and he was not handing them out as a private citizen but a public official. This is proselytizing on the job and this is not allowed. Now not all Christians have an insane persecution complex like the ones this movie is made for. Now you could argue; "But if you hate this movie then why would you watch it?" Like, for real? If so, then there is something seriously wrong with the U.S.A. When I was a kid, I often heard about the U.S.A. being a country of freedom, of liberty. In U.S. movies, I heard Americans proudly speaking about their country. But now that I am an adult, I often see that this or that is banned in the U.S. Things that are so common in our country. Things like having the right to keep chickens in your garden, even in cities. Or planting veggies in your garden, etc. And now - Jesus is banned in the U.S.??? Since when? Who and when banned speaking of Him anywhere? I mean, it would be silly to speak about Jesus being God in a muslim mosque. But in schools? Where is the freedom of speech? Where is the freedom of belief? Which stupid president or government produced such an evil thing?
